<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911213-0120</DOCNO><DOCID>911213-0120.</DOCID><HL>   Cox Buys 12.5% Stake   In Fiber-Optic Unit   From Merrill Lynch</HL><DATE>12/13/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MER</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)SECURITIES (SCR)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. said it completed the saleof a 12.5% stake in its fiber-optic network business to mediacompany Cox Enterprises Inc. Terms weren't disclosed.   The fiber-optic subsidiary, Teleport Communications GroupInc., operates private fiber-optic communication networks in17 major business centers in and around the largest U.S.cities. Such networks are popular with corporations and otherlarge organizations, which are heavy telephone users and arereluctant to rely on local phone companies as a single sourceof service for transmitting voice and data messages.</LP><TEXT>   As previously reported, the companies in June reached anagreement for Cox to buy the stake, and said they wouldprovide Teleport with an additional $80 million forexpansion. Atlanta-based Cox, with interests in newspapers,broadcasting and cable television, is interested in thepossibilities of fiber-optic lines for carrying televisionsignals, which could provide new markets for information andentertainment. Also, recent regulatory moves could result inallowing the private networks to link up with local phonesystems.</TEXT></DOC>